<paragraph blockId="42.[121,225,1154,1179]" box="[121,225,1154,1179]" pageId="42" pageNumber="381">
<emphasis box="[121,225,1154,1179]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="381">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="42.[121,1089,1205,1440]" pageId="42" pageNumber="381">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Giron &amp; Franz" authorityYear="2010" box="[121,334,1205,1231]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Apodrosus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="381" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viridium">
<emphasis box="[121,334,1205,1231]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="381">Apodrosus viridium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized by the combination of a relatively small size (2.5– 3.5 mm), a reduced and linear median furrow on the head, a shiny green uniform scale coverage (excepting the legs which have pink scales), and straight, erect, yellowish setae on the elytra. This species may be differentiated from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Giron &amp; Franz" authorityYear="2010" box="[739,826,1309,1335]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Apodrosus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="381" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="artus">
<emphasis box="[739,756,1309,1335]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="381">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[772,826,1310,1335]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="381">artus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its uniformly green colored dorsal vestiture. It furthermore differs from the similarly colored 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Girón &amp; Franz" authorityYear="2010" box="[949,1089,1343,1370]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Apodrosus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="381" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stenoculus">
<emphasis box="[949,966,1344,1370]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="381">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[982,1089,1343,1369]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="381">stenoculus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the presence of a linear median furrow on the head, long erect elytral striae, and widely oval (as opposed to narrow, linear) eyes in lateral view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
